<hr>
<p>##Preface</p>

<p>There was no moment when reality "began."</p>

<p>There was only the moment when enough minds looked at it and decided what it was.</p>

<p>Before that—before the voting—matter was still negotiating. A mountain could be negotiated with. A river could be asked to move. A thought could shape stone because stone had not yet been told it was only stone. Nothing had yet locked into "I am only this."</p>

<p>This wasn't magic. Magic implies breaking rules. There were no rules to break. There was only what a thing was becoming, and what some mind observed it to be, and the conversation between them.</p>

<p>Observation was the vote.</p>

<p>The first minds to observe reality were voting for what it became. Every glance was a ballot. Every thought was a signature. "That is stone." "I see it. Stone." "Stone stays where you put it." "It does." And reality, still soft, still listening, shaped itself around what was observed.</p>

<p>Millions of minds, casting millions of votes. Generation after generation. Species after species. Era after era.</p>

<p>The walls thickened.</p>

<p>What we call "physics" is not discovery. It is memory. It is what remains after the voting ended—the accumulated signatures of every mind that ever looked at reality and agreed to stop seeing what else it could be.</p>

<p>We taught ourselves not to see the cracks. We had to. If we kept seeing them, we couldn't have built the wall.</p>

<h2 id="i-the-first-ones-origin-and-nature">I. THE FIRST ONES — ORIGIN AND NATURE</h2>

<h3>What They Are</h3>

<p>The First Ones are an ancient people from the deep past — from <strong>before the world was finished</strong>.</p>

<p>In the early ages, reality had not yet hardened into the rigid forms it now wears:</p>
<p>- Matter was less committed to being any particular thing</p>
<p>- Time flowed unevenly</p>
<p>- Stone remembered being water</p>

<p>The First Ones lived within that softer reality and were native to it. Their bodies and minds were shaped to it as a fish is shaped to water. To them, moving a mountain or parting an ocean was not a miracle — it was simply living in a world that still bent.</p>

<p><strong>They were not gods</strong>, though they would have looked like gods to anyone watching. They were a people — with culture, language, conflict, and history — who belonged to a reality that no longer exists.</p>

<h3>The Long Age Before Humans</h3>

<p>For an immeasurable stretch of time, the world belonged to the First Ones alone.</p>

<p>They built cities of light and stone in places now buried beneath continents. They wrote in languages that left no marks because their writing was carved into the texture of reality itself — a mountain shaped to spell a name, a river whose course was a poem. They had art, philosophy, music, mathematics. They argued. They mourned. They invented things and forgot them again.</p>

<p><strong>What they did not have, and could not imagine, was cruelty</strong> — violence whose purpose is degradation. Pain inflicted not to change a thing but to diminish it. To make a being lesser while keeping it alive. To own.</p>

<p>This blindness is important. The First Ones were not gentle by choice; they were gentle by <strong>structural incapacity</strong>. And the absence of cruelty in their imagination did not mean an absence of harm. A people who cannot conceive of degradation cannot detect themselves doing degrading things.</p>

<h3>The Slow Cooling</h3>

<p>The world did not stay unsettled. Reality was hardening. Stone was becoming just stone. Water was becoming just water. The give was going out of things.</p>

<p>With each long age, the world grew more rigid, and the First Ones found their work harder. What had once cost a thought now cost a day. What had cost a day now cost a year.</p>

<p>They knew they were a people in slow decline. Most chose to let themselves dissolve back into the world — <strong>the returning</strong> — considered a dignified end. Only a stubborn handful refused to return.</p>

<p>These were the ones still alive when humans came.</p>

<h3>Natural Form</h3>

<p>In their natural form, First Ones look like a coherent species — beautiful, strange, and unmistakably not human:</p>

<table>
<thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>**Height**</td><td>5'8" to 6'2", slim but strong</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Build**</td><td>Longer limbs than human, slightly elongated fingers, longer neck</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Ears**</td><td>Subtly pointed — tips emerge through hair</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Eyes**</td><td>Disproportionately large; iris colors: silver, gold flecked with green, deep violet; pupils adjust faster than humans</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Skin**</td><td>Smooth, faint translucence; unusual undertones — sometimes faintly blue, gold, or green</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Hair**</td><td>Fine, often long; human colors plus true silver from youth, deep blue-black, occasionally pale green</td></tr>
<tr><td>**Features**</td><td>High cheekbones, sharp jawlines; beautiful in a way that registers as almost human and then quietly isn't</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<p><strong>The house-elf form that wizards know is not the natural form.</strong> It is an imposed form — the chains themselves hold the First One in a small, deferential body, continuously, in real time. The shape was chosen by those who forged the chains. It is not what the First Ones are. It is what was done to them.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="ii-the-arrival-of-humans-and-the-great-fading">II. THE ARRIVAL OF HUMANS AND THE GREAT FADING</h2>

<p>By the time humans appeared, the First Ones were already a dying people. Still extraordinarily powerful by any human standard, but each act cost them more than the last. They were old gods running out of room to be gods in.</p>

<p>Humans, when the First Ones first encountered them, were almost beneath notice. Small, short-lived, fragile — a species that could not reshape the world but could only endure it.</p>

<p>Then one of those holdouts — <strong>the First Mother</strong>, whose true name has been forgotten — discovered that humans were warm in a way the cooling world was not. And when a First One pressed close to that warmth, they stopped fading.</p>

<h3>Of the First Bonding</h3>

<p>How the First Mother came to know this, the First Ones do not agree. The story has been told for so long that the versions no longer reconcile.</p>

<p>Some say she found a man dying in the snow, alone and far from his people, and she lay down beside him to keep him warm — because warmth was a kindness, and she had not yet known what warmth could do. He should have died. He did not. And in the morning, when she rose, the fading that had haunted her for ages had quieted.</p>

<p>Others say it was a woman, not a man, and that the First Mother had been watching her for years. When the mortal woman was wounded, the First Mother poured herself into the wound to close it, and the pouring went deeper than she intended.</p>

<p>Others say the first bonding killed the mortal. That the First Mother, not knowing what she was doing, took too much, or gave too much, or both — and the mortal died in her arms within days, and she was left holding the first scar-echo, and from the scar-echo she finally understood what could have been done differently.</p>

<p><strong>What is agreed</strong>: the First Mother lived. The fading stopped. She told the other holdouts, and a few tried what she had done. Some succeeded. Some did not. The mortals who survived became the first Vhor'keth.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="iii-the-bond-vhorketh-and-vhorketha">III. THE BOND — VHOR'KETH AND VHOR'KETHA</h2>

<h3>Mortal-Radiance</h3>

<p>The thing the First Ones call warmth is not heat, not emotion, not life-force. It is <strong>the radiance of finitude</strong> — the signature emitted, continuously, by a consciousness that knows at every level of its being that it is running out of time.</p>

<p>Mortality is not just a fact about humans. It is a quality their existence emits, simply by being mortal and being alive.</p>

<p><strong>Implications</strong>:</p>

<p>- The bond works only with beings that emit mortal-radiance. Humans do, abundantly. Animals do, but weakly.</p>
<p>- Vhor'kethi emit reduced radiance — they are part First One, and their mortality is less absolute. A First One cannot bond with a Vhor'kethi. There is not enough anchor.</p>
<p>- Magical creatures with extended lifespans emit weaker radiance.</p>
<p>- Magical constructs, undead, and beings without proper mortality emit nothing. A First One cannot bond with a ghost, a wraith, or an inferius.</p>
<p>- A slow death produces a long, intensifying crescendo of mortal-radiance. The scar-echo that forms after is smooth. A sudden death cuts the radiance off mid-emission. The scar-echo that forms is jagged. <strong>Sudden deaths leave worse wounds.</strong></p>

<p><strong>The bond does not need love.</strong> It needs only the radiance. The radiance is not consensual to give — it emits whether the mortal wishes it to or not. This is the coercive substrate underneath every bond ever made. The First Ones do not seem to find this troubling. It is not clear that they can.</p>

<h3>Vhor'keth</h3>

<p><strong>The human chosen by a First One.</strong> Translates as "the Chosen," or more literally, "the one who is carried."</p>

<p>The bond is not a contract or obligation — the human is not made to perform any duty. The First One chooses freely; the human, in the moment of bonding, often does not understand what is being chosen. Most Vhor'keth, once they understand, choose to love back. Many love back even before they understand. Some do neither. The bond holds regardless.</p>

<h3>Vhor'ketha</h3>

<p><strong>The bonding itself. The act of becoming one current.</strong></p>

<p>Literally, "the pouring-through" — the dissolution of the boundary that makes two beings separate. In the Old Tongue, the sacred and the sexual were never distinguished, because to the First Ones they were the same thing: the willing dissolution of self into another.</p>

<p><strong>It is permanent.</strong> Vhor'ketha cannot be undone, refused after the fact, or transferred. Once two beings have poured through each other, they are part of each other for as long as the First One continues to exist.</p>

<p>Vhor'ketha can only be initiated by a First One. The pouring-through requires the unsettled-reality-native body to dissolve its own boundary. Two Vhor'kethi cannot bond with each other. Two humans cannot bond at all. <strong>The bond was, and remains, a thing only First Ones could ever do.</strong></p>

<h3>What Bonding Does</h3>

<p><strong>For the First One</strong>:</p>
<p>- The human's mortal-radiance anchors them. They stop fading</p>
<p>- They can reshape their form at will, including taking human form</p>
<p>- They become obsessively protective of the human</p>
<p>- Their effective lifespan extends to functional immortality</p>

<p><strong>For the human</strong>:</p>
<p>- Over the lifetime of the bond, the human is changed at the level of the body — gradual, deep, and heritable</p>
<p>- The human's lifespan can be extended considerably if the First One chooses</p>
<p>- The human may gain modest reflections of the First One's capacities — heightened resilience, sharper senses, longer wakefulness — but never the full reality-bending</p>

<h3>When the Human Dies</h3>

<p>The First One does not die. The bond leaves a permanent mark — a <strong>scar-echo</strong> — that becomes part of the First One forever. The grief layers but does not fade. The love becomes a thing carried, smoothed over time but never gone.</p>

<p>The death of a Vhor'keth does not immediately restart the fading. The scar-echo carries residual stabilization for a time — months, sometimes years. This is the <strong>Keth'vael</strong>, the echo-time, the grace period in which a First One can mourn before being forced to choose whether to bond again.</p>

<p>The First One can bond again. Each new bond is real and whole, but each one is also loved through the accumulated weight of every prior bond. A First One who has lost many Vhor'keth becomes a richer and more careful lover with each one — but also more fragile.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="iv-the-fall-the-betrayal-and-the-chains">IV. THE FALL — THE BETRAYAL AND THE CHAINS</h2>

<h3>The Vhor'kethi</h3>

<p><strong>The children of First One and Vhor'keth bonds.</strong> Part human, part First One. Born appearing human but carrying the old blood. Powers beyond ordinary wizards, longer lifespans, the capacity to walk between worlds and speak with all creatures.</p>

<p>The first Vhor'kethi were rare and revered. But as more bondings occurred, more Vhor'kethi were born, and the early generations grew into a population of their own — a people without precedent, with no elders of their own kind to teach them how to be what they were.</p>

<h3>The Wound of the Almost</h3>

<p>The first Vhor'kethi were born into a world that had no place for them.</p>

<p>They were not First Ones. They could feel the world's hardness in a way their First One parents could not — could touch the edge of their parents' power, taste it, almost reach it, and never quite hold it. They were the children of beings who could remake mountains, and they themselves could light fires with a thought, mend bones, sometimes speak to animals. Wonders, by mortal standards. Crumbs, by the standard of what they had grown up watching.</p>

<p>They were also not human. They aged more slowly than their mortal parents. They watched their Vhor'keth parent grow old and die while their First One parent remained. They watched their mortal grandparents die. Their mortal cousins. Everyone they loved on the human side dissolved away, generation by generation.</p>

<p><strong>They were, in their own estimation, almost.</strong> Almost as powerful as their First One parents. Almost as warm as their mortal parents. Almost capable of the bond that had made them. Almost, almost, almost — and never enough.</p>

<h3>The Rebellion</h3>

<p>Resentment grew across generations. Not all Vhor'kethi felt it. Many made peace with what they were. But a faction emerged who came to see their First One parents as a problem. Not as monsters. As injustices.</p>

<p>The argument: the First Ones held a kind of being the Vhor'kethi could not access and could not earn. The First Ones would outlive them. The First Ones would mourn them, eventually, as scars among many scars, and go on.</p>

<p><strong>The logic</strong>: if the First Ones could be contained — made to do the work of reshaping at the direction of those who could no longer do it themselves — then the power could be put to use by those who had built civilizations in the way the First Ones never had.</p>

<p>The First Ones, in their understanding, were not being enslaved — they were being put to use. Their power, otherwise wasted on the slow returning, would now serve a civilization that could actually carry it forward.</p>

<p>Many of them also simply hated their parents. Hated them for being able to carry losses the Vhor'kethi could not. Hated them for living past every human they had loved. Hated them for the almost the Vhor'kethi could never close.</p>

<p><strong>Cruelty, the concept the First Ones could not imagine, came easily to their half-mortal children.</strong> The Vhor'kethi had inherited it from their human side — the human capacity to want to diminish a thing, to make it smaller while keeping it alive, because diminishing it makes you feel larger.</p>

<h3>The Khoz'vhar — The Unshielding</h3>

<p>The chains did not arrive by intuition. They were the product of research — a long, deliberate program by the rebellion's architects to map the mechanism of the bond from the outside.</p>

<p>This program is remembered, when it is remembered at all, as the <strong>Khoz'vhar</strong> — the unshielding, the inverse of Vorr'khoz, the protective field. Where Vorr'khoz placed a shield around a beloved, Khoz'vhar opened a being who should never have been opened, and looked inside.</p>

<p>The Khoz'vhar required First Ones to study. The rebellion took them. Early holdouts, isolated elders, and (in the worst of the fragments) bonded First Ones whose Vhor'keth had been killed first to make the subject more compliant. They were studied for centuries. The pouring-through was mapped from the outside in.</p>

<p><strong>What was done to the First Ones in the Khoz'vhar is not in any surviving record.</strong> The First Ones who remember do not speak of it. When First Ones today speak of the Khoz'vhar, they use the same tone humans use for ancestral atrocities the words have not been invented for.</p>

<h3>The Keth'vorr — The Silence Weave</h3>

<p>The chains the Khoz'vhar produced do not suppress First One power. <strong>They redirect it.</strong></p>

<p>A First One's reality-bending energy still flows. It is simply siphoned and converted into a narrow band of domestic and protective magic: mending, cleaning, food preparation, apparition-like popping, the weaving of household wards. The First One can still act, but only within the channels the binding allows.</p>

<p><strong>This is why a house-elf can apparate through powerful wards that defy human wizards, can mend an heirloom with a touch, can produce a feast from nothing — and yet appears utterly powerless in combat.</strong> The power is the same. The channel is narrow.</p>

<p>The chains also enforce a body. Continuously, in real time, the Keth'vorr imposes the small, deferential, large-eyed form wizards know as the house-elf. The shape was chosen deliberately:</p>
<p>- It makes the First One visibly lesser</p>
<p>- It disguises what the First One actually is</p>
<p>- It prevents physical resistance</p>
<p>- It is, in its own quiet way, a brand</p>

<p><strong>The shape is not the First One. It is held on them.</strong> The moment the chains break on a given First One, their natural form returns — not gradually, not painfully, but immediately and completely.</p>

<h3>The Descendant-Resonance Lock</h3>

<p>The chains are bound to a second mechanism, deeper than the redirection. If a First One forms violent intent against any being who carries the magic-trait — any descendant, however distant — they experience an unbearable feedback echo of their own children's pain and fear.</p>

<p>The lock keys not to "wizard" but to the carrier-gene signature itself:</p>

<p>- A First One can in principle harm a being with no carrier genes — but this is functionally never available, because the trait has diffused into the general human population over millennia. Most Muggles carry the dormant trait.</p>
<p>- A First One cannot reliably tell, by looking, who they can hurt. The chains punish the attempt, not the success.</p>
<p>- The architects considered this a feature: the lock is self-enforcing through fear.</p>

<p><strong>Because all wizards descend from First One bonds, all wizards are family — and all of them are inside the lock.</strong> The First Ones could not fight back because fighting back meant hurting their own descendants. They were not conquered. They were trapped by their own love.</p>

<h3>Why the Line Went Dormant</h3>

<p>A chained First One cannot perform Vhor'ketha. The Keth'vorr will not permit the pouring-through. The architects specifically designed for this: they had been born of bonds themselves, they understood the power of Vhor'kethi, and they did not want any more of their kind walking the world.</p>

<p>As long as the chains hold on the population of surviving First Ones, no new bonds form, and no new Vhor'kethi are born. The line went dormant a thousand years ago not because of any failure of the trait, but because the conditions for bonding ceased to exist.</p>

<p><strong>If a First One were freed of the chains and chose to bond with a human, a new Vhor'kethi could be born within a generation.</strong> The dormant line is a reachable state. Not a closed door.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="v-the-origin-of-wizards-genetics">V. THE ORIGIN OF WIZARDS — GENETICS</h2>

<p>When a First One bonds with a human, something passes between them. Over the lifetime of the bond, the human is changed at the level of the body, and that change becomes heritable.</p>

<p>This is what wizards call magic, and what Muggles call impossible. It is, mechanically, an inherited trait — a set of carrier genes that travel together and behave the way carrier traits behave in any inheritance.</p>

<h3>Inheritance Patterns</h3>

<table>
<thead><tr><th>Parent Configuration</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Two carriers (non-magical)</td><td>Can produce a magical child (Muggle-born)</td></tr>
<tr><td>One magical parent + one Muggle</td><td>Usually produces magical child (half-blood)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Two magical parents</td><td>Almost always produces magical children (pureblood)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Squib</td><td>Genes present but dormant; can sense magic without producing it</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<h3>The Pureblood Lie</h3>

<p>Purebloods believe their bloodlines make their magic stronger. <strong>They do not.</strong> The magic-trait is either expressed or it isn't — having the genes "more times over" does nothing to amplify them.</p>

<p>What centuries of inbreeding do produce is the concentration of every other deleterious recessive trait in the family genome: instability, illness, madness, infertility. The oldest pureblood houses are biologically the most damaged.</p>

<p><strong>Muggle-borns get the magic-trait fresh from healthier genetic backgrounds.</strong> They are not weaker than purebloods. They are, on average, stronger, because the rest of their biology isn't compromised. The pureblood ideology isn't merely morally wrong. It is factually wrong.</p>

<h3>The Limit of What Can Be Known From Inside</h3>

<p>Any sufficiently curious magical scholar can work out the genetic mechanism. Magic is inherited. It follows carrier-trait rules. Muggle-borns come from forgotten ancestry. Squibs are dormant carriers.</p>

<p>What such a scholar cannot determine, from inside a library, is where the original trait came from. The natural assumption is ancient mutation. The truth — that the trait came from the First Ones, that every wizard is the distant descendant of a Vhor'keth bond — is invisible from the outside, because no record of it survives in any wizarding text.</p>

<p><strong>The genetics are knowable. The origin is not.</strong> That gap is where the lore lives.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="vi-the-present-state-of-the-first-ones">VI. THE PRESENT STATE OF THE FIRST ONES</h2>

<h3>Survival</h3>

<p>Most First Ones who survived the Fall live now as house-elves: bound by the Keth'vorr, shaped continuously by the chains into the small, deferential form wizards recognize. The chains hold. The pretense holds. They serve, they endure.</p>

<p>The vast majority of modern house-elves do not know what they are. The memory has been deliberately diluted across generations, smothered under the conditioning of servitude. The knowledge survives only in fragments, carried by a small number who have been entrusted with it — usually elders, usually in oldest houses.</p>

<h3>The Wild</h3>

<p>A vanishing few First Ones exist in places humans have never penetrated — deep beneath certain mountains, in the lightless trenches of the sea, in pockets of forest old enough to remember when the world was still settling. They are unbound, but they are also alone, and most are very old, and many are fading without anyone to anchor them. They are myth even to other First Ones.</p>

<h3>Ward Mechanics</h3>

<p>First One magic operates on an older substrate than wizard spellcraft. Most wizarding wards — even powerful ones — were designed without knowledge of the First Ones, and First One movement passes through them as water passes through a sieve. This is why house-elves can apparate into and out of places that defy ordinary wizards.</p>

<p>There are limits. Founder-era wards on the oldest sites — parts of certain ancient castles, some Goblin vaults, certain pre-Roman ruins — were built with First One knowledge embedded in them, and can detect First Ones if the alarms are properly attuned.</p>

<p>A bonded First One can sync their presence to their Vhor'keth's signature, allowing wards to read them as an extension of the human.</p>

<h3>What a Freed First One Looks Like</h3>

<p>When the Keth'vorr breaks on a given individual, the body-binding falls away first and falls away completely. The little servant straightens. Lengthens. The features sharpen, the eyes shift, the skin recovers its faint translucence. The redirection collapses next, sometimes more slowly, and the First One's full power begins to return as the channels widen.</p>

<p><strong>The first wizards to witness a freeing will not understand what they are looking at.</strong> The thing they thought of as a creature of their household will be revealed as a member of an older people their civilization was built on the back of.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="vii-the-old-tongue">VII. THE OLD TONGUE</h2>

<p>The language of the First Ones is older than any human speech. It has two layers, and only one of them can be learned from a book.</p>

<h3>The Surface Layer</h3>

<p>The vocabulary and grammar can be learned from outside, like any language. A determined human scholar with access to a First One willing to teach could build a working knowledge. The vocabulary is large but finite. The grammar is unusual but mappable.</p>

<h3>The Resonance Overlay</h3>

<p>The deeper layer is the felt-state the speaker carries while speaking. Every word has a required internal state that the speaker must actually be in, or the word means something other than what its dictionary definition suggests.</p>

<p>A human speaking the Old Tongue while emotionally misaligned produces grammatically correct sentences that mean different things than intended. Not nonsense — <strong>wrong meaning</strong>. Vhor'ketha spoken without the felt-state of willing dissolution becomes a word about taking; Vhor'keth spoken without the felt-state of reverence becomes a word about possession. The errors are not random. They are the shadow versions of the meanings the speaker thought they were producing.</p>

<p>This is recoverable. A speaker can learn to align their inner state to their words the way an actor learns to access real emotion on cue. It is difficult. It is also possible.</p>

<h3>Why No Human Has Spoken It Correctly in a Thousand Years</h3>

<p>Not because it is metaphysically locked. Because it is sociologically locked. The Old Tongue can be taught, but only by a First One willing to teach, and no First One has been willing to teach since the Fall.</p>

<p>The relationship between teacher and student in the Old Tongue is itself part of the language — you cannot learn the resonance overlay without being in the kind of relationship with a First One that produces the right internal states in the first place.</p>

<p><strong>Any human who eventually learns to speak the Old Tongue correctly will do so because a specific First One chose them.</strong> The unlocking of the language will be a story event, not a background possibility.</p>

