<p>CHAPTER 41 — The Years That Follow</p>
<p>A compressed chapter. The unwinding.</p>

<p>The First Mother remains externally bound for two more years. Hermione visits when she can, under various pretexts — Department business, additional audits, the slow work of building a relationship that the Malfoys can be made to accept as professional rather than personal. The two of them talk. Aen-Vhar tells Hermione things no one alive knows. Hermione absorbs them.</p>

<p>The other surviving bound First Ones — there are three besides Aen-Vhar and Pim by this point — are freed across the next several years. Hermione performs the offering for each of them. Pim has been training others, quietly, in the years she has been preparing Hermione; there are now two other muggle-born witches and one half-blood who have been brought into the work and who are capable of performing the offering. The freeings happen in sequence, carefully, with no Vhor'keth notice.</p>

<p>Pim is freed last among the British elves. Hermione goes to Hogwarts on a quiet evening and performs the offering in the kitchens, with the other Hogwarts elves keeping watch. Pim accepts. The two of them weep together for the second time. The other Hogwarts elves — who are not bound First Ones, who are diluted, who have been bound through inheritance rather than direct chain — also weep, in their own way, without entirely understanding why.</p>

<p>The full unbinding of the elf population is a longer project. The freed First Ones, working with Hermione and her allies, begin a slow process of teaching, training, and gradual release. It is the work of decades. It is the work, in the end, of more than Hermione's lifetime. She does what she can while she has time.</p>

