<p>Hermione nods. She cannot speak.</p>

<p>They sit in the garden as the light goes out of the day.</p>

<p>The book ends with the First Mother walking alone in a forest, some years after Hermione's death. She is speaking in the founding Old Tongue to those she carries. She speaks to the father, as she has every day for six thousand years. She speaks to Hermione, as she has every day for the past several. She tells them about her day. She tells them about her grandchildren — Hermione's grandchildren, whom the First Mother has chosen to consider her own, because she has earned the right to choose her family across the long ages. She tells them about the slow ongoing work of the unbinding, which is now well underway across the world, which Hermione started and which will outlast Hermione and outlast the First Mother and outlast everything that is currently alive in the wizarding world.</p>

<p>The wind moves around her, the way it used to before the Fading was strong.</p>

<p>She keeps walking.</p>

<p>The book ends.</p>

